<br>
He grabeed a handful of coins and threw them at the bard, perhaps a bit harder than was really necessary.  The clatter of the coins on the stage interrupted the bard's music and he turned to look at Kalaz.<br>
<br>
&quot;Play something else,&quot; Kalaz said, &quot;And if I ever hear you playing that song again, you'll be eatin' your drum for dinner.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Um, of course, sir,&quot; the bard replied, &quot;What should I play?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You're an elf, play something elvish.&quot;  Kalaz said as he turned back to his drink.  He signalled to the bartender to bring him another while the elf started playing in the background.  It was something soft and sappy, a love song of some sort.  It didn't matter, as long as it never mentioned snow the dwarf didn't mind.  It was a simpleenough somg that he could almost ignore it completely, sense it as a quiet drone in the background.<br>
<br>
Halfway through the chorus, two thing happened at almost the same instant.  The door to the tavern opened and the bard missed a note in the song.  Either one would have been easy to ignore, but together they provided just enough of an interruption that Kalaz paused in his drinking for a moment to look up.<br>
<br>
A Dark Elf.  In the bar.  Wonderful, he thought, the one place in the whole damn city he could go to get a quiet drink and now they were admitting Dark Elves.  He appreciated the Coldain attitude, such as it was.  Everyone was considered suspect until they proved themselves one way or another.  The unterusted ones wold be watched closely, and perhaps cheated a bit by the locals, but they were left alone until they showed their true colors.  While that was al fine and good for the inhabitants of Thurgadin, it was a bit uncomfortable for the people coming from Antonica or Faydwer.  Many of them, himself included, had still not gotten used to the idea of sharing a bar with a Troll or Ogre...or a Dark Elf.<br>
<br>
The Dark Elf looked around the tavern casually before making his way to the bar.  Right next to Kalaz.<br>
<br>
&quot;Barkeep,&quot; the Elf said, &quot;Bring me a bottle fo your best wine.  If you have anything back there worth drinking and not just swilling down.&quot;  <br>
<br>
He sneered slightly at Kalaz and his ale just as the elf missed another note in the second verse of the song.<br>
<br>
The barkeep ignored it as he brought out a bottle of wine and poured a glass.  The Dark Elf took a snip, a slight look of distaste crossed his face.<br>
<br>
&quot;This will do, I suppose.&quot;  The Dark Elf pushed his cloak back as he reached across his body to get his purse.  The bard in the corner missed another note in his song (it was quickly becoming apparent why he had chosen to stick to singing the simple Coldain songs).  Kalaz looked over at the Dark Elf, noticing the odd movement nad saw the reason for it.<br>
<br>
The Dark Elf was missing his left hand.<br>
<br>
&quot;Right, then.&quot; Kalaz said.  He drained his mug, set it down softly and turned in his chair to face the Dark Elf.<br>
<br>
The Dark Elf looked down at him haughtily, raised an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes?&quot; he said sarcastically.<br>
<br>
Kalaz punched him in the jaw as hard as he could.<br>
<br>
The Dark Elf crumpled to the ground, unconscious.  He hopped off of his stool and turned to the bartender.<br>
<br>
&quot;Was that really necessary?&quot; the bartender asked as Kalaz fished out some coins.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye,&quot; Kalaz said, &quot;It was.  I have this feeling the gods are trying to tell me something.&quot;<br>
<br>
The barkeep nodded in understanding.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well then.  If it's the will of the gods, then that's all there is to it.&quot; he said as he collected the coins off the bartop.<br>
<br>
&quot;So,&quot; Kalaz said as he wrapped his cloak around his shoulders, &quot;Who do I talk to about booking passage on the Icebreaker?  It seems it's time for me to head back to Antonica.&quot;<br>
<br>
